# Next.js full-stack project initialization in 2025

Modern Next.js project scaffolding has evolved dramatically with **Turbopack becoming the default bundler in Next.js 16**, **Tailwind CSS v4 adopting CSS-first configuration**, and **Biome emerging as a faster alternative to ESLint + Prettier**. The best initialization scripts now leverage these advances while providing sensible defaults for auth (Auth.js v5), database (Prisma with connection pooling), and testing (Vitest over Jest). This report covers concrete patterns and configuration snippets for each area.

---

## CLI scaffolding tools compared

The official `create-next-app` has added significant options in 2024-2025, including **React Compiler support** (`--react-compiler`), **Biome as a linter option** (`--biome`), and **Turbopack enabled by default**. Running `npx create-next-app@latest` now presents these choices interactively:

```bash
npx create-next-app@latest my-app \
  --typescript --tailwind --eslint --app \
  --src-dir --turbopack --react-compiler
```

**create-t3-app** remains the gold standard for full-stack type-safe applications, offering modular selection of **tRPC**, **Prisma or Drizzle**, **NextAuth.js**, and **Tailwind CSS**. The key innovation is generating only what you select—not a monolithic template. For production SaaS applications, **next-forge** provides the most comprehensive starting point with Clerk auth, Prisma + Neon, Stripe payments, React Email, and monitoring pre-configured across multiple apps (main app, docs site, marketing site).

Turborepo starters structure monorepos with `apps/` for Next.js applications and `packages/` for shared code like `@repo/ui` (component library), `@repo/eslint-config`, and `@repo/typescript-config`. This pattern separates concerns while enabling efficient caching.

